          <article>
            <header>
              <h2>Why Is It Worth Tracking Your Mood?</h2>
            </header>

            <p>Every day we experience a range of emotions — from euphoria to sadness, from calm to stress. But can you
              really say why you feel the way you do? Do you know how often it happens? How it affects your relationships,
              work, sleep?</p>
            <p>This is where mood tracking comes in.</p>

            <h3>What are the benefits?</h3>
            <p>1. Greater self-awareness</p>
            <p>Regularly noting your mood helps you understand what influences your emotions — people, situations,
              times of day, even the weather. It’s the first step to living consciously.</p>
            <p>2. Better stress management</p>
            <p>When you notice what causes stress or discomfort, it becomes easier to avoid those situations or respond
              to them more calmly.</p>
            <p>3. Therapeutic support</p>
            <p>If you’re seeing a psychologist or psychiatrist, a regular mood journal is a treasure. It helps the
              therapist spot patterns faster and choose better treatment methods or areas for personal development.</p>
            <p>4. Motivation to take care of yourself</p>
            <p>When you see on a chart that certain activities (e.g., a walk, meditation, talking to a loved one) really
              improve your mood, you’re more likely to repeat them.</p>

            <h3>How to start?</h3>
            <p>You don’t need anything complicated. Just:</p>
            <p>- 2 minutes a day,</p>
            <p>- an app like EchoMood (😉),</p>
            <p>- the willingness to take care of yourself.</p>
            <p>Start with a simple question:</p>
            <p>“How do I feel today?”</p>
            <p>And add a short note — what happened, how you reacted, whether there was a reason.</p>

            <h3>In conclusion</h3>
            <p>Remember, your emotions matter. Instead of ignoring them — become friends with them.
              With a simple tool like a mood journal, you can build a better relationship… with yourself.</p>
          </article>

        </div>
      </div>

